        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "src": "__GHOST_URL__/content/images/2021/07/GM-Still-Won-t-Help-You-Hack-The-C8-Corvette--2.jpg",
        "width": 1920,
        "height": 1080,
        "caption": "photo credit: GM"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Anyway, Tadge Juechter, Corvette Executive Chief Engineer, was interviewed by Muscle Cars and Trucks recently and he said what we’ve heard over and over: GM won’t be helping anyone hack the C8’s ECU. Sure, it’s for security purposes or something like that, even though thieves seem to have no problem hacking and stealing C8 Corvettes.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Juechter has quite the diplomatic thing to say about the situation. “The aftermarket crew is very talented and resourceful,” he stated, then went on to say that’s why GM won’t throw them a bone to “protect our customers.”",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "src": "__GHOST_URL__/content/images/2021/07/GM-Still-Won-t-Help-You-Hack-The-C8-Corvette--3.jpg",
        "width": 1920,
        "height": 1080,
        "caption": "photo credit: GM"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "But it was only a few years ago General Motors tried using The Digital Millennium Copyright Act (DMCA) passed in 1998 to go after 2 aftermarket parts suppliers for offering vehicle control modules with unauthorized copies of GM’s software on them. It was a complicated case you can read more about ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 0,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": "here",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              }
            ],
            "direction": "ltr",
            "format": "",
            "indent": 0,
            "type": "link",
            "rel": null,
            "target": null,
            "title": null,
            "url": "https://lrus.wolterskluwer.com/news/ip-law-daily/gm-fails-to-state-copyright-infringement-and-dmca-claims-against-auto-parts-sellers/32599/",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": ", but the point is the company doesn’t exactly have a great record when it comes to supporting owners tuning their own cars how they see fit. As enthusiasts, we have a problem with that, a big problem. We expect the C8 Corvette is being used as a testbed for rolling out this kind of strategy for other vehicles in the future.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
